Dirty lens / Dirty Windows / Sunflare - I have to apologize to my Tamron zoom lens. I take back anything I sad bad about that lens. I prefer prime lenses so it doesn’t get much use! I grabbed it yesterday and it had so much dust on it, so I wiped it with a cloth. Well, the smears on it must have produced these fun flares, along with the dirty windows. Each time I have used this lens, it has produced something unique. I need to use it more creatively!

Christmas🎄with Polaroid Instant Camera! I need LOTS more practice w my new @polaroid Now + camera! I’m so so so excited, bc my first camera was a Polaroid, and it made me fall in love w photography as a child! I have scrapbooks full of Polaroids from the 80’s that I cherish! These were quick snaps before I read about how I can actually control exposure to a point w the Polaroid app. I can’t wait to experiment more with this camera!

Shadow Self-portrait Series / #intheshadows_nq / I did not create enough for this series this past year, but that is ok. This past year was a year to pause and have grace with myself. I feel so blessed and grateful to have had a year to recuperate from awful burnout unrelated to photography, and to be able to focus on cultivating my relationships w friends and family. I went to something like 15 concerts, which fills my soul, and sometimes had a little too much fun! But ya know, it was good for me. Concerning photography, I tried not to put too many goals on myself this past year, but am proud that I’m finally using film regularly. I hope to use my camera much more in 2023, and get a bit more focused. 🌿🌿🌿

Flawed / Polaroid Series / I’m very excited about changing gears a bit with my work. I’m taking a class with Yan Palmer at the moment, and I’ve already learned so much; my head is spinning surrounding taking the steps to cultivate my voice. It’s good though. I’ve talked about my love of Polaroids in the past, and I finally have the emotional and physical space to dive into new projects. I’m hoping to start using a vintage camera to shoot Polaroid film, but this was taken with a @polaroid now plus.

35 mm film / Dance - Lookout Kid / Portra 400 / Film loop / a little intentional camera movement to try and exaggerate the movement going on here. I forgot to post this w a record series Coop and I did w some Police albums from my youth. Yet, I spoke about my love of the new Arcade Fire album this past summer and the most fitting song for this photo would be Unconditional I on the WE album. It’s a song I sing to my boys and the message is so beautiful. 
.

You can dance, and you can shake

Buy, sell, trade / thrift store / Montrose Avenue / 35 mm film / Houston / @thefindlab / I cannot emphasize enough how happy film makes me! Also so thrilled to finally be doing more street work. I took these about a month ago in a cool area in Houston on Montrose Avenue, where there are hip restaurants, bars, and plenty of thrift stores. I’ve been going here for years, and used to study for tests in a coffee shop nearby. I think I’m hooked on street photography now! Anywho, I’m anxious to put all the photos from this series in one post because my tags have not been working half the time. Stay tuned for more from this series.  @thefindlab @ilfordphoto

Rugged Beauty on 35 mm film | CHANDRA | On the rocks | Women over 50 | Finding Wonder Mexico 2023 | In our youth obsessed culture, women over 50 are often underrepresented; Youth is so connected to beauty and “attractiveness” in our culture, and as we age, some older women may feel left out, invisible, or simply unattractive due to the unattainable standards of beauty. Yes, there is so much more to women than beauty, and the definition of what is beautiful varies vastly. These incredible women in this series have embraced their age and exude a palpable and powerful beauty that can only come with life experience. Their life stories speak of pain, loss, and enormous grief, but also of incredible strength, joy, and wisdom at what they have seen, achieved, and overcome. I love how these enormous rock structures, with all of their crevices and curves carved out in time, are symbolic of the depths of beauty within these women. I’ve been so grateful to have had such incredible adventures, healing sessions, belly laughs, and freaking fabulous fun with my beautiful soulful friends @finding.wonder @chandra.sandoval and @cindyknightphoto are such an inspiration as women, and I’m so happy that I was able to collaborate and photograph them and my other FW sisters in this fashion.  @thefindlab @ilfordphoto

2 Polaroids | Self-portrait | Loop | 👈🏼👈🏼👈🏼2023 was a year of roadblocks with my art. So, I’m starting 2024 with an imperfect Polaroid. Last year was to be filled with new projects, one of which focused on hacking a vintage camera and using Polaroid film. Well, it seemed that each time I really pushed myself, running like a giddy school girl to execute these exciting creative visions that fill my head, I would hit a technical roadblock and was unable to continue w some of my creative journeys. That said, I am blessed that 2023 was filled w travel, friends, and time w my family. I was able to photograph with primarily film, which makes me happy. I was not very drawn to Instagram for various reasons, but I so crave an art community. While I created less, I feel I’ve grown in my work, and I was happier w my photos.  I was published, and that is always a main goal! Well, this a self-portrait, created on a whim, which is how I work best. While I’ve been wanting to experiment w self-portraits using this hat, I hadn’t planned on it that day. When I saw the amazing winter light streaming into my bedroom, I went into my closet, and grabbed this vintage blouse of my mother’s along with her hat that hangs on a console in my bathroom. The hat was also handy as I hadn’t washed my hair in a few days, ha! I used the portrait mode on the Polaroid Now plus and crossed my fingers. Here is to bulldozing over roadblocks and figuring out my vintage camera in 2024.
